deck_name: Combo Guide to Yugioh's Strongest FTK - Volcanic Snake-Eye FTK
deck_excerpt: Possibly the strongest, most reliable burn FTK ever conceived, Snake-Eyes Volcanic FTK reduces your opponent's LP by 8800!
deck_description:
Possibly the strongest, most reliable burn FTK ever conceived, Snake-Eyes Volcanic FTK is a particularly nasty, resilient and consistent 1 card FTK made possible by the recent support cards released in the Blazing Arena selection pack. With a singular Snake-Eyes Ash, 8800 burn damage is possible during your first turn (3000 burn) and during your opponent's draw phase (5800 burn), before your opponent has the chance to potentially do any action. Masterduel's single game format renders this FTK particularly potent, since it's main weakness "siding" isn't possible with a best-of-1 format. Bonfire has just been added to Masterduel as well, adding another layer of consistency to this already powerful FTK!
 
Technically it is "not" a FTK since the burn combo completes in your opponent's turn - your opponent still cannot do anything to stop your double burn trap onslaught with Volcanic Emission + Spiritual Fire Art - Kurenai from activating to inflict 5800 burn (unless they somehow have the extremely rare Red Reboot). 
 
The crazy thing is that if this FTK gets interrupted with say, a handtrap, this strategy can easily pivot into regular Snake-Eye gameplay. When a FTK's back-up plan is a tier 1 strategy, this makes the it incredibly powerful and adaptable. 
 
It is recommended that you attempt this FTK going only first or in a very simplified gamestate - otherwise just play Snake-Eyes regularly. 
 
If you want a detailed guide on Snake-Eyes, check out one of my earlier articles by clicking here!
 
Otherwise, here is the Snake-Eyes Volcanic Burn FTK combo: 
 
Snake-Eyes Ash = 8800 burn damage (3000 burn during your turn + 5800 burn during your opponent's draw phase). 
 
  1. Normal summon Snake-Eyes Ash. Snake-Eyes Ash searches Poplar.
  2. Activate Poplar's effect to summon itself from hand when it is added to hand. 
  3. Activate Poplar's on-summon effect to search from deck Original Sinful Spoils. 
  4. Link summon Linkuriboh using Poplar.
  5. Activate Poplar's effect to place itself in the backrow. 
  6. Activate Snake-Eyes Ash's effect using Poplar in the backrow to summon from deck Flamberge Dragon. 
  7. Activate Flamberge Dragon's effect to place in the backrow a monster. 
  8. Activate Original Sinful Spoils sending the backrow monster to summon from deck Volcanic Rimfire. 
  9. Link away Flamberge Dragon + Rimfire to summon I:P Masquerena. 
  10. CL1 Flamberge Dragon to summon Ash and Poplar from the GY, CL2 Rimfire to banish itself to send from deck to GY a Volcanic Trooper. 
  11. Link away Linkuriboh + I:P Masquerena to summon Promethean Princess. 
  12. Activate Promethean Princess' effect to summon from GY Volcanic Trooper. 
  13. Activate Volcanic Trooper's on-summon effect to search for Volcanic Emperor from deck. 
  14. Activate Volcanic Trooper's discarding Volcanic Emperor to summon a Bomb Token to the Middle Main Monster Zone to your opponent's field. 
  15. Link away Volcanic Trooper + Promethean Princess to summon Amblowhale. 
  16. Link away Snake-Eyes Ash to summon Relinquished Anima. 
  17. Summon from deck Awakening of the Possessed - Greater Inari Fire sending to GY Relinquished Anima and Poplar. 
  18. Activate Greater Inari Fire's on-summon effect using your opponent's bomb token to inflict 1000 burn damage. (Opponent has 7000 lifepoints left). 
  19. Link away Greater Inari Fire + Amblowhale to summon Geonator Transverser to your left Extra Monster Zone. 
  20. Greater Inari Fire searches for Spiritual Fire Art - Kurenai from deck since it was sent from field to GY. 
  21. Summon Volcanic Emperor from the GY using any combination of pyro monsters (Greater Inari Fire + Volcanic Trooper + level 1 Snake-Eye). Summon Emperor to the leftmost Main Monster Zone, the zone that Geonator Transverser is pointing to. Volcanic Emperor inflicts 2000 burn damage since 4 pyro monsters are banished and sets Volcanic Emission from deck. (Opponent has 5000 lifepoints left). 
  22. Activate Geonator Transverser's effect to switch the positions of Volcanic Emperor and Bomb Token. 
  23. Summon Linkuriboh from GY by tributing Bomb Token. 
  24. Link summon another Promethean Princess using Geonator Transverser and Linkuriboh. 
  25. Set Spiritual Fire Art - Kurenai. 
  26. During your opponent's drawphase, activate Volcanic Emission targeting Volcanic Emperor controlled by your opponent (inflicts 3100 burn damage - Opponent has 1900 lifepoints left) and activate Spiritual Fire Art - Kurenai tributing Promethean Princess (inflicts 2700 burn damage - Opponent has -800 lifepoints left)! This totals 8800 burn! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
 
Even if interrupted, this deck can either keep extending to complete the burn combo, or pivot to regular Snake-Eye gameplay. Going second, this deck functions as a regular Snake-Eye deck - handtrap your opponent to slow them down and gas gas gas your way forward with the ridiculously powerful and resilient Snake-Eye cards! 
 
Have fun cheesing your way to the top of Masterduel ladder with this ridiculously powerful and reliable FTK burn deck!

A combo deck that attempts to end on Runick Fountain, S:P Little Knight, Baronne de Fleur, and Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying.

Most hands uninterrupted can go into S:P + Baronne (or Chengying), others can go into just Fountain + S:P.

Combo Line 1: S:P + Either Synchro + World Chalice + Runick Fountain

Any Runick Spell (except Fountain) + Any lvl 3 (Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Chosen by the World Chalice, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit)

The most common hand assuming you don't draw World Chalice or you drew runic + hand traps:

Play any runick spell to special Hugin, activate Hugin to grab Fountain, play Fountain, Normal any lvl 3, Synchro into Ib (in the EMZ), Ib grab World Chalice, link the EMZ Ib into Gravity Controller, Ib special Chosen from deck, link Chosen into Imduk, Extra Normal (tributing Gravity Controller) World Chalice, link World Chalice + Imduk into Aurum, special Lee + Guardragon (put Guardragon in one of Aurum's link arrows), Lee grab World Chalice, activate Aurum to pop Guardragon, special from grave Ib, link Lee + Aurum into Lib, Aurum effect to special World Chalice from hand, Ib + World Chalice synchro into either synchro monster, Lib effect to set World Legacy Heart, activate World Legacy Heart to put Ib back into ED and World Chalice to hand, Guardragon in GY effect to special Chosen to a Lib arrow, link Chosen to second Imduk, link Lib + Imduk into S:P, activate Imduk effect to special World Chalice.

Combo Line 2: S:P + Either Synchro

Chosen by the World Chalice + World Legacy - "World Chalice" 

If you somehow only have World Chalice and Chosen w/ no Runic Spells (or Hugin gets removed before you can use it as synchro material):

Normal Chosen, Link Chosen into Imduk, Extra Normal World Chalice, Link World Chalice into Almiraj (Ash chokepoint), Special Chosen + Lee from World Chalice effect, Lee grab Guardragon, Synchro Chosen + Lee into Ib 5* (under Almiraj), Ib grab World Legacy Heart, Activate World Legacy Heart to return to hand Chosen + World Chalice, Activate Lee in GY to add to hand while sending Guardragon, activate Guardragon to special Chosen to Almiraj's link arrow, Link Chosen into second Imduk, link Imduk + Almiraj into Lib, Imduk effect special World Chalice from hand, Activate Lib to set World Legacy Succession, synchro Ib + Chalice to make a Baronne/Chengying, special World Chalice from Ib effect, link Lib + World Chalice for S:P.

Combo Line 3: S:P + Both Synchro + Runick Fountain

Any Runick Spell (except Fountain) + Emergency Teleport + any World Chalice monster (except World Chalice Guardragon)

This route is one of the strongest you can get, ending with 2+ cards in hand while having Fountain + both synchros + S:P. If you are lucky, you also can end with World Chalice though it rarely happens due to interaction. The World Chalice search is also chainblocked by Imduk for safety.

Play any runick spell to special Hugin, activate Hugin to grab Fountain, play Fountain, play Emergency Teleport and grab either Ghost Ogre or Chosen, Synchro into Ib (in the EMZ), Ib grab World Chalice, link the EMZ Ib into Gravity Controller, Ib special Chosen from deck, link Chosen into Imduk, Extra Normal (tributing Gravity Controller) World Chalice, link World Chalice + Imduk into Aurum, CL1 World Chalice -> CL2 Imduk, Imduk summon the extra World Chalice monster to a zone away from Aurum, special Lee + Guardragon (put Guardragon in one of Aurum's link arrows), Lee grab World Chalice, activate Aurum to pop Guardragon, special from grave Ib, link Lee + Aurum into Lib, Aurum effect to special World Chalice from hand, Ib + World Chalice synchro into either synchro monster, Lib Effect to set World Legacy Succession, activate World Legacy Succession to summon Ib, Ib + World Chalice synchro into the other synchro monster you didn't summon before, Guardragon in GY effect to special Chosen to a Lib arrow, link Chosen to second Imduk, link Lib + Imduk into S:P.

deck_excerpt: A Light/Warrior domain deck that helps the other players...
deck_description:
Fundamentally, this is a deck about deception, as fits the date it was built on (April Fool's)

With Neo Space Connector, the opening is special summon Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin to link into Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights 

From there, search to hand either Courageous Crimson Chevalier Bradamante or Sasuke Samurai #3 from Isolde's effect. And then use Phoenix Gearblade and Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade for Isolde's cost to special summon Two-for-One Team. Gearblade returns to hand by its effect being sent for the cost of a monster effect.

Reveal Gearblade in hand for Two-for-One Team's effect, and more than likely everyone at the table will want the free cards.

Next turn, use Isolde to special summon Sasuke Samurai #3, and use Chevalier's effect to discard and equip the Shooting Star Bow - Ceal to Sasuke Samurai, as well as the Phoenix Gearblade. Poke another player directly whoever wants to draw until they have 7 cards by Sasuke's effect.

At this particular point, being mechanically helpful and with a seemingly single purpose and gimmicky deck makes it extremely easy to be underestimated, especially amidst the active threat of the other players. And it can be fun to play into the shop gimmick using and recycling Gold Moon Coin for providing various equip spells to other players.

That said, there are three possible lines to actually get a win.

The first is if Sasuke Samurai #3 survives, Mage Power and other equip spells on top of the Shooting Star Bow may allow it to simply swing directly for game. Or, as a variant for pure fun, tribute summon Millennium Shield and use Magnum Shield along with various other equip spells and swing for potentially high damage that way. Armed Samurai - Ben Kei is also an option instead.

The second is if Infinite Cards is in play, the hand sizes of the other players will enable Arcana Triumph Joker to have ridiculously high attack.

The third is using Mikanko Kagura to potentially burn for quite a bit given the excess of equip cards in this deck. Otherwise, Ohime the Manifested Mikanko can make for a dangerous comeback.

But as might be expected with this kind of a deck, it's not for anyone that really wants to win. It's objectively inconsistent and gimmicky. But sometimes it's enjoyable just to help the other players have fun.

deck_name: Mc Coolia e as Fadas do Tamborzo
deck_description:
(Para total compreensão desse tutorial, veja a primeira versão do deck)

 

Primeiramente, qual o motivo de fazer uma nova lista? Pois bem, desde a versão anterior do deck muita coisa mudou, joguei muito com algumas caryas novas e consegui alcançar algum domínio sobre essas cartas, e a agora você deve estar dizendo "Mas ei! Quase nenhuma carta do deck mudou, não tem motivo para essa lista nova!!" é aí que tudo começa kkkkkkk.

Pois bem, quem vos escreve sou eu... O seu JadenBR da shopee, e vim solucionar ou piorar seus problemas com esse arquétipo (vulgo o melhor do mundo, apenas aceitem!), então vamos ao que realmente interessa, o deck!

E já começamos assim kkkkkkk cara, uma carta, literalmente uma carta fez as Solfachords pularem de um deck que talvez surpreenda, para um deck que definitivamente vai surpreender uma galera (obviamente falando de pessoas que não estão jogando com o absoluto meta), e a carta que estou falando é a Materialization (todos os nomes das cartas estarão em inglês para facilitar pra vocês acharem elas por aí) essa carta é simplesmente absurda para as Solfachords, pois todo o plano de jogo do deck gira em torno de uma quantidade X de monstros em campo para iniciar qualquer um dos combos do deck, desde os mais básicos até os mais complexos.

Mas porque Materialization é tão forte para as garotas? Bem, essa carta faz realmente tudo o que o deck quer fazer, que é special summon fácil e praticamente de graça. Por conta do deck ser focado em penduluns, é normal iniciar com pelo menos dois penduluns na mão, e unindo essa informação com essa carta você consegue fazer normal summon de um pendulum e special summon do outro usando a Materialization. Por essa special summon extremamente simples, você deve (sim, deve!!) rodar 2-3 Materializations, a carta literalmente pega todo o deck e o cola juntinho, por isso nunca use menos de 2 cópias dela, 3 eu entendo que pode sim dar um brickzinho, mas por favor menos de 2 cópias não, a carta ta baratinha, veio comum.

Outra mudança importante, saída de um Riseheart e agora rodando 3 Fenrir, por que? Não adianta tentar bater de frente com os decks de fogo, então é melhor ir pela consistência do que pela diferença, mas a Gradielle continua por que ela é boa, simples assim kkkkkkk também por que não tem tantas opções de xyz level 7 realmente incríveis, e xyz level 7 é o mais fácil de fazer nesse deck, e sobre o Fenrir, na pior das ocasiões ele é uma interação com o campo do oponente.

Outra alteração importante, mais handtraps e menos traps. Por causa da Materialization facilitando o special summon dos pendulum as handtraps acabam por se tornam peças de combo além de interações contra o oponente.

Saída do Avramax para a entrada da Apollousa, bem, essa mudança é uma questão puramente de gosto, eu particularmente prefiro ter mais opções defensivas do que ofensivas, e a Apollousa se encaixa muito bem nisso, além de ser muito boa contra decka focados em criaturas.

De mudanças grandes na estrutura do deck foi isso, parece pouco mas o deck passou a rodar de forma quase que totalmente diferente  após essas mudanças, se tornando muito mais confiável e consistente. O deck passou de 5-6 bricks a cada 10 mãos para 1-2 bricks a cada 10 mãos, isso sendo azarado (E olha que eu gosto de rodar deck com 45 cartas kkkkkkk aliás, mudem isso no de vocês, tirem algumas handtraps e deixem o mais próximo possível de 40 cartas, eu rodo 45 porque sou doido mesmo kkkkkk) (Sobre brick, minha concepção de brick é bem extrema, para mim brickar é não fazer nada, baixar tudo e passar, uma interação que seja para mim já não é mais brick).

Agora vamos a algumas opções para baratear k deck na medida do possível (essas opções vão seguir os preços dispostos no marketplace da LigaYuGiOh) começando pelo Crystal Wing, o Clear Wing Synchro Dragon faz um papel bem parecido e é bem mais barato (esse também sendo opção para fazer na mão usando a Harmonizing ao invés do efeito da trap do Z-ARC). A parte de monstros link pode se tirar a S:P Little Knight e colocar o Knightmare Unicorn sem nenhum problema,  a Underworld Goddess pode ser uma opção excelente para a Apollousa, Borrelsword Dragon é um finisher que as pessoas esqueceram sobre mas ainda faz o trabalho dele.

Sobre os extenders como os Kashtiras, é válido usar a engine de Darkwurm e os gates, mas com atenção para não travar suas zonas pendulum, pois a Gran Coolia usa um solfachord de scale ímpar para ativar seu omni negate, fiquem espertos. Sobre a Baronne e o Savage, dá para mudar eles por literalmente qualquer synchro, mas se atente a mudar também o alvo da Harmonizing para ela puxar o nível correto para fazer a synchro summon. Vou destacar aqui como opções o Geomathmech Final Sigma, a Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen, o Stellar Wind Wolfrayet, o F.A. Dawn Dragster, o Black Rose Dragon, e por fim a retornante Ib The World Chalice Justiciar.

Sobre linhas de combo, essa parte é complexa, pois veja bem o deck tem dezenas e talvez centenas de variações para os os combos, e essa descrição já está quilometrica kkkkkkk então vou colocar aqui a linha mais básica de combo e confio em vocês para aprenderem mais (algum dia no futuro, bem no futuro mesmo eu faço um vídeo exemplificando tudo o que eu falo por aqui).

Linha mais básica possível, termina em uma Gran Coolia ativa: Cutia e Dreamia na mão - Normal summon Cutia buscando uma Coolia - Pendulum scale Coolia - Special summon Dreamia usando seu efeito - Dreamia e Cutia para fazer Beyond The Pendulum - Efeito Beyond buscando outra Cutia - Pendulum scale Cutia - Pendulum summon Dreamia - Dreamia e Beyond para fazer Gran Coolia.

A partir daqui você consegue fazer quase todos os combos do deck, mas não se prendam a essa linha, joguem, estudem, experimentem o deck vocês também, aprender o deck vai além de memorizar linha de combo, e sempre se lembrem com um deck de menos intensidade como as Solfachords qualidade de interações é mais importante que quantidade.

Bem, essa é a nova versão do deck, peço perdão pela demora, mas assim que cartas novas saírem para o TCG eu venho aqui atualizar a lista, essa descrição era pra ser maior mas não consegui copiar o meu texto pra cá e tive que reescrever tudo kkkkkkk por isso, qualquer dúvida, sugestão, ideia, comentem aí que eu responderei o mais rápido possível. É isso, paz! ^o^

It is wild that I didn't post this already. While elysium is surrounded by the "isn't it just busted" meme in domain format this deck is actually a culmination of alot of my time with the game. Being main comprised of shaddolls and invoked as well as some random engines I just enjoy. This deck very much encompasses me as a player. 

It is nice that while alot of the bosses are fusions the extra deck isn't actually that necessary for the deck to function. I am a fan of tool boxy midrange decks and generally I can lean into that. with solid engines and some really cool 1 of cards that people generally just aren't ready for (ie: ordeal of the traveler)

Unlike wombo elysium decks this deck doesn't have the wild build a boards but it does regularly have play on each other players turns. and also unlike other elysium decks I do actually get to use the deck master even though it isn't every game. 

If you ever want to catch a game go check out the discord!

HOUDINI Format:

  • $10 Main & Extra Deck Limit: Combined cost under $10 based on TCGplayer's cheapest listings.
  • $3 Side Deck Limit: Allows for strategic adjustments with a separate $3 budget. Best of 3.
  • Excludes Pendulum & Link Monsters: Simplifies gameplay, focusing on strategy. Card pool includes other new cards however.
  • Must Include 1 Field Spell & 1 Normal Monster: Encourages diverse deck-building.
  • Designed for Accessibility & Strategy: Rewards card knowledge over monetary investment.
  • Old and New: New cards, older playing style - an evolution of Edison Format.

deck_excerpt: This is the deck I run for fun the extra deck is just some other fun cards that I use every now and then.
deck_description: This is the deck I run for fun.  The extra deck is just some other fun cards that I use every now and then.
ZONE LOCKED
Aqua and Shark Base

Deckmaster: Sentinel of the Tistina 
Domain Restriction: WIND // LIGHT // AQUA

Main Combo:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-59140332 

Intro:

The Tistinas, despite their unflattering results in the TCG, possess traits that translate fantastically into the longer-length games of Domain Format. 
Most notably, and quite possibly most importantly, Hound of the Tistina and Sentinel of the Tistina can resummon themselves once-per-turn from the GY without the condition of banishing themselves when they leave the field. This provides a near-infinite amount of material that can used for Extra Deck Plays, Tribute fodder, and general utlity. 
In addition their ablity to close grindy games is nailed in by Hound of the Tistina, which allows every Tisitna to attack directly. This nails the coffin on many opponents who have been worn down by battles of attribtion. 
Tistinas also focus rather heavily on removal of face-up spell/trap cards with their Main Deck bosses Crystal God Tistina and Demigod of the Tistina. Removing continous spells/traps deny the long-term value our opponents may be relying on to win the game. 

To recap, Tistinas have several advantages that work fabously for Domain Format:

  1. Swarming the Field from the GY
  2. Attacking Directly to close games
  3. Removal of pesky spells/traps opponents may play

We combine this strategy with the Majespecters and Gate Guardians to complete the deck.

Here is what this deck is capable of doing:

  • Consistantly remove both set and face-up spells/traps
  • Access Gate Guardian Boss Monsters in order to make use of powerful cards such as Riryoku Guardian and Gate Guardian of Wind and Water 
  • Set Pendulum Scales, with Pendulum Monsters in the Extra Deck ready to be summoned
  • Consistantly XYZ Rank 3 or Rank 4 with Hound of the Tistina/Sentinel of the Tistina and a Pendulum monster
  • Search relevent Field Spells for our needs

Catagory Breakdown:

Revival:
Aquarium Stage, Aquarium Set, Back to the Front, Call of the Haunted, Oasis of Dragon Souls, Play of the Tistina, Xyz Reborn, Scrap-Iron Sacred Statue        

Gate Guardian: 
Elemental HERO Prisma, E - Emergency Call, Fusion Deployment, Flock Together, Labyrinth Wall Shadow, Riryoku Guardian, Double Attack! Wind and Thunder!!   

Change to Face-Down:
Book of Eclipse, Book of Moon, Floodgate Trap Hole, Breath of the Tistina, Embrace of the Tistina, Paleozoic Canadia     

WHAT DO WE WANT TISTINA TO DO?

  • Destroy Spell/Traps with Crystal God Tistina or any other Tistina Boss
  • Put Tistina, the Divinity that Defies Darkness into GY to be revived
  • Provide free and easy fodder for XYZ or Synchros ( Hound of the Tistina )
  • Close games through direct attack ( Hound of the Tistina )

As deckmaster, Sentinel of the Tistina always guarentees that we have access to the entire Tistina lineup. From powerful continous traps like Embrace of the Tistina, to the devestating Graveyard removal trap that is Discordance of the Tistina, Sentinel of the Tistina's arsenal is truly vast. 
This speaks nothing of the awestriking power of Demigod of the Tistina, able to easily devestate unprepared boards. However the real meat is Tistina, the Divinity that Defies Darkness who can, on special summon, remove all set cards from our opponent. Notably, this effect is tied to special summon and not just XYZ summon, which leads to an boost in power for every Revival Spell/Trap we use. 
Tistinas form the backbone of power in this deck. 

Combo:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-59140332 

WHAT DO WE WANT MAJESPECTERS TO DO?

  • Provide free material for XYZ summon
  • Search Field spells ( Majester Paladin, the Ascending Dracoslayer )
  • Access utlity spells/traps ( Majespecter Cyclone, Majespecter Tempest, etc.)  

Majespecters are easy to access with the advent of their new Rank 4 Majespecter Draco - Ryu who can be made generically using any 2 level 4 monsters (this deck contains lv4 monsters that can be special summoned from hand). Majespecter Draco - Ryu has a restriction where its effect can only be used if a monster is tributed; fortunely Tistinas have us covered! By using Sentinel of the Tistina to seach out Tainted of the Tistina, we are able to tribute our opponent's monster in order to trigger Majespecter Draco - Ryu's effect to special summon the Majespecter we need to get things started. 
Majespecter Orthrus - Nue does everything for the archtype -- they set scales and dumps Pendulum Majespecters into the extra deck on summon. The most important Pendulum to summon is  Majesty Pegasus, the Dracoslayer, who searches a field spell on summon. We will do this using Majespecter Draco - Ryu's twice per turn effect, this time proc-ing it through use of Majespecter Wind.

In the end of things, we will have set scales, Pendulums in Extra Deck to summon, utlity spells/traps, and a field spell in hand.     

Combo: 
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-59140451 

HOW AND WHY: GATE GUARDIAN  

  • It is just funny to play them
  • Gate Guardian of Wind and Water negates 2 spells/traps per turn
  • Riryoku Guardian can easily do upwards of 3000 points of direct damage

Gate Guardian cards to hard to access. This deck creates them by using a series of steps in order to get the required materials on field as continous spells, to summon either Gate Guardian of Thunder and Wind or Gate Guardian of Wind and Water. These steps pivot through their field spell, Labyrinth Wall Shadow, and are long winded in the fact that they cannot happen unless all the previous steps of Tistina and Majespecters have suceeded. We also have other contingities in the form of Flock Together, which puts a Gate Guardian as a spell/trap, and Elemental HERO Prisma, which copies the name of a Gate Guardian.   
Once here however, Gate Guardian of Thunder and Wind can easily add Riryoku Guardian to hand, which then cuts an opponent's LP and sysnergizes with the Direct Attack Capablities of Tistinas in order to quickly dispace a foe. 
Overall, Gate Guardian provide a nusiance that is hard to find in any other Archtype. 

Combo: 
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-59140592 

THE EXTRA DECK 

  • Exosister Mikailis can add Exosister Arment to summon Exosister Asophiel on either player's turn. This locks down the GY for a turn, stopping any recursion engine that our opponent may have been relying on.
  • Gold Pride - Captain Carrie can add Gold Pride - Better Luck Next Time! which adds Gold Pride - Leon to hand, allowing us access to Synchro Plays
  • Ancient Fairy Dragon can add the Labyrinth Wall Shadow which helps our Gate Guardian Plays
  • Baronne de Fleur can be made by using Hound of the Tistina + Sentinel of the Tistina + any lv3 Tuner. This is easy because Hound and Sentinel can Special Summon themselves from GY
  • Daigusto Emeral can shuffle back Crystal God Tistina to the Deck so it can summoned out once more using Divine Domain Baatistina

Other Cards: 

  • Thunder Dragon Titan can be special summoned using Gate Guardian of Thunder and Wind, which adds a spell like Double Attack! Wind and Thunder!!, which then adds Sanga of the Thunder to hand. This furfills the requirment of 1 Thunder Fusion monster on Field and a Thunder monster in Hand. 
  • Aquarium Lighting can be destroyed from field using our deckmaster, Sentinel of the Tistina's cost. This will activate its effect to special summon an aqua from GY
  • Magical Hats//Foolish Burial Goods  can send Aquarium Set, Flock Together, Rainbow Bridge of Salvation, Interrupted Kaiju Slumber or Double Attack! Wind and Thunder!! depending on which GY effect we want to use most. 
  • Diana the Light Spirit and Munin the Runick Wings are our LP gain cards to weather the storm of long Domain games. 
  • The cards that put things face-down synergize with Tistina cards such as Tainted of the Tistina and Crystal God Tistina 
  • Rainbow Bridge of Salvation should be easy to activate due to the fact we have several lv10 monsters in the form of Baronne de Fleur, Crystal God Tistina, Thunder Dragon Titan, and Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju

High Level Machine/Psychic deck for Domain Format, a casual multiplayer free-for-all format inspired by MTG Commander format.

Using Psychic Processor as the Deck Master gives me access to DARK, Machine, Psychic or Cyberse monsters.

The main goal of this deck is to spam Psychic Processor to summon all the monsters you can from your hand, attack directly and then go for a Xyz Summon if needed. Each time you use your Deck Master, you're going to add it back to your hand by his own effect in the next Standby Phase, so you don't to worry about the Deck Master tax.

How do you put Ruinforce in the GY? 
Machina Gearframe + Machina Unclaspare, Machina Air Raider, Machina Irradiator, Machina Fortress, Machina Redeployment, Revolving Switchyard and Graceful Charity.

Synergies:

  • Cyber Dragon + DNA Surgery/Clockwork Night: Go for Chimeratech Fortress Dragon using the board. Pair with Heavy Storm for maximum efficiency.
  • Number XX: Utopic Dark Infinity + any BIG special summoned monster: Maybe this is the best way to gain LP in the deck. Your best targets are Machina Ruinforce, Number 77: The Seven Sins, Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora and Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe.
  • Number 97: Draglubion + Number 92: Heart-eartH Dragon and Number C92: Heart-eartH Chaos Dragon
    • Number 92: Heart-eartH Dragon: Summon this one if you need to pressure the table with his banish effect or the reflect damage. 
    • Number C92: Heart-eartH Chaos Dragon: Summon this one if you need to gain LP or need a board negate.

Notable techs:

  • Revolving Switchyard: A search for our High Level Machines and enable Rank 10 plays.
  • Psychic Arsenal: Pay 600 LP to add any of your DARK Machines? Yes please!
  • Original Bamboo Sword: Remember! You can attack directly with your DM's special summoned monsters during that turn, add this for a surprise Raigeki.
  • Limiter Removal: Old but GOLD! 

Cards for further testing:

  • More High Level Machines like Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon, Snow Plow Hustle Rustle, Carnot the Eternal Machine, etc.
  • C-3PO and R2-D2.
  • Maybe more Gizmeks.
  • Decanelogue - Valdrath, Number 95: Galaxy-Eyes Dark Matter Dragon and Number 9: Dyson Sphere.

We play on the Domain Format discord often. Anyone can come ask questions or learn the format to build a deck.

Also you can check Yugioh Commander!'s rules video down below.

deck_excerpt: The best way to play Ashened with the current card pool imo
deck_description:
The deck is still a work in progress, looking forward to seeing what the new Ashened support will consist of.

 

The goal of the deck is to brute force through hand traps, it can brick if you draw too many ashened cards or horus monsters without a way of getting them out of your hand.

I usually try to bait out hand traps with ashened combos which if uninturrupted can get you to a rank 8 or rank 4.

The Banshee exists to set up the volcanic or horus plays by either searching Volcanic Shell or Volcanic Emperor, could also be used in rare situations to search for Veidos or another Ashened monster.

Using Volcanic Emission on Veidos that your opponent controls can further choke them, if you also have Volcanic Emperor and some Horus monsters on board as they will need to deal with the Emperor without triggering the Horus monster's effects.

deck_name: Ironclad Beast Brigade: Fortune Favors the Bold!
deck_excerpt: Charge into destiny with the Ironclad Beast Brigade! Beastly fury meets Machine mastery and every flip can unleash the firepower of fate!
deck_description:
Ironclad Beast Brigade: Fortune Favors the Bold!

March into battle with the unstoppable might of metal and magic, as the Beast Warriors unveil their latest marvel – the awe-inspiring Desperado Barrel Dragon. A symphony of clanking armor and whirring gears, this structure deck fuses the untamed spirit of beasts with the precise calculations of a machinist's mind. Flip the coin, channel the energy, and let the power of fusion guide you to glorious victory. With flips that decide fates and spells that charge your arsenal, in this brigade, bravery meets brilliance on the battleground. Spin the cylinder, take aim with your enchanted engines, and let destiny unfold – for in the Ironclad Beast Brigade, only the bold are victorious!

• Unleash Mechanical Mayhem: Use "Desperado Barrel Dragon" and "Barrel Dragon" to control the board with their coin flip effects, annihilating your opponent's cards based on heads or tails.

• Ramp Up the Power: Employ "Limiter Removal" and "Power Bond" to double, or even quadruple, the ATK of your Machine monsters for a turn, potentially delivering game-ending blows.

• Fusion Frenzy: Combine your monsters with "Power Bond" to summon "Pair Cycroid" or "Panzer Dragon" for a massive surge in field presence and offensive capability.

• Master Your Fate: Utilize "Second Coin Toss" and "Cup of Ace" to tip the scales of chance in your favor, ensuring your coin flips result in the outcome you desire.

• Resurrect and Revolt: Take advantage of "Monster Reborn" to bring back your powerful monsters from the GY for another round of chaos.

• Clear the Path: Use "Dark Hole" to wipe the slate clean when the field gets too crowded, setting the stage for your machines to march through.

• Magical Backup: "Mystical Space Typhoon" provides the spell/trap disruption necessary to protect your brigade from pesky backrow threats.

• Protect and Serve: "Rare Metalmorph" and "Metalmorph" not only boost your monsters' ATK but can also protect them from targeted effects, making your mechanical warriors tougher to take down.

• Optimize and Enhance: "Machine Assembly Line" and "Terraforming" ensure that your resources are consistently flowing and that your mechanical army is always at peak performance.

• Stand Your Ground: "Prepare to Strike Back" gives your monsters a second wind, readying them for a counteroffensive after weathering your opponent’s attacks.

• Direct the Assault: "Heavy Armored Train Ironwolf" can give your machines direct access to your opponent’s life points, bypassing their monsters entirely for a potential finishing move.

 

• Strategic Resilience: "Gachi Gachi Gantetsu" bolsters your monsters' defenses, providing a sturdy wall against your opponent’s offensive efforts.

Tags:
Beast-Warrior, Coin Toss, Barrel Dragon, Coin Flip, Chaos, Houdini Format, Machines, Fusion, $10 Deck, Budget Deck, Casual, Structure Deck, 

HOUDINI Format:

  • $10 Main & Extra Deck Limit: Combined cost under $10 based on TCGplayer's cheapest listings.
  • $3 Side Deck Limit.  Best of 3.
  • Excludes Pendulum & Link Monsters, Master Rule 3. Card pool is based on currently released cards.
  • Must Include 1 Field Spell & 1 Normal Monster.
  • Card Knowledge as a resource, accessible on a budget. 
  • Old and New: New cards, older playing style - an evolution of Tengu Plant Format.

deck_name: Cyber Dragon Superheavy Samurai (Duelist Messiah - YugiNoNo)
deck_excerpt: Cyber Dragons may be getting support in Duelists of Brilliance, so I wanted to make this variant of CD before any support comes out! Enjoy!
deck_description:
So in March 2024, the duelist pack Duelists of Brilliance came out, giving Trickstars and Tachyon some much-needed support! This Duelist Pack is meant to provide legacy support for LIGHT-based archetypes that appeared in any of the "Yu-Gi-Oh!" anime. And you know what archetype is full of LIGHT monsters? One of YugiNoNo's favorite archetypes, Cyber Dragons!

 

Cyber Dragons basically have old man strength. They're a tad outdated nowadays and rely on other archetypes (Branded, Horus, Cyberdark, etc) and techs (Carnot the Eternal Machine, Kashtira Fenrir, Clockwork Night, etc) to do their best. Despite that, the archetype has enough offensive options to deal a lot of damage. 

 

One engine that can help out Cyber Dragons is Superheavy Samurai. 3 Motorbike, 3 Wakaushi, 1 Big Benkei, and 1 "Superheavy Samurai Soul" monster, depending on the deck you're splashing it in. Cyber Dragon Core, Herz, and Nachster are all Level 4 or lower Machine monsters, so this deck uses 1 Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster. With this engine, Cyber Dragons can summon Gear Gigant X and search Core, Herz, or Nachster all without using your Normal Summon yet. As an added benefit, it's easy to summon Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon and Baronne De Fleur, giving this deck another out to Nibiru. 

 

So with that in mind, this deck uses the Superheavy Samurai archetype to either search Core/Herz/Nachster, or summon an omni-negate. On top of that, the deck has 9 hand traps, and 2 copies of Power Bond, so if you have to go 2nd, you're still capable of going on the offensive. And as for the Side Deck, you can smokescreen your opponent and turn the deck into Clockwork Cyber Dragons.
Illusion Chimera (Apr 2024)

deck_excerpt: Be the BOSS and trigger Ragnarok on ladder with Generaider Runick!
deck_description:
Generaider has been a rogue option for years since it's release back at 2019 with the deck build pack Mystic Fighters. In turn, it's lore-related sister archetype Runick has released in Tactical Masters in 2022. There has always been a connection in the archetypes with Loptr and the respective Generaider bosses appearing in the artworks of both archetypes, but there never has been a competitively viable way to mix both archetypes... Until now!!!
 
With the release of the Masterduel Selection pack Blazing Arena comes the last crucial piece to connect both archtypes - Sleipnir the Runick Mane. 
 
Summonable by any Runick quick-play spell, this noble steed is a level 9 - an additional free body to assist with Generaider combos! This allows for easier access to Laevatein, Generaider's "XYZ superpoly," or it allows for the "double handloop -> F0 Utopic Draco Future" combo to be easier to accomplish. It is banishing interruption which helps clear boards. On top of that, it also generates tokens everyturn, just like Generaider Boss Stage!

Sleipnir is a definitely a force multiplier when combining both Generaider and Runick together - allowing for the creation of a incredibly powerful grindy control strategy! 
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
As the name implies, Generaider Runick is mainly composed of the two archetypes. 

The GENERAIDER part of the strategy is composed of 17 cards. It's role is to spam out as many level 9 bodies as possible for R9NK 9 plays. If you can summon 2 level 9 bodies, Laevateinn is usually the best play, since it has the incredibly powerful removal effect to attach anything in the field/GY as a quick effect - essentially  a "xyz super poly." During the occassional time when you can summon four level 9 monsters (usually helped by World Legacy Monstrosity/Runick Spell summoning Sleipnir), the double handloop with Enterblathnir -> Utopic Draco Future is the ideal play. During your opponent's turn, Generaider Boss Stage summons Harr for an omni-negate or Utgarda for a banish. Repeat plays every turn until you have your opponent defeated by your superior grindgame! 
 
RUNICK offers an alternative win condition of this deck by banishing your opponent's deck. Runick also increases the deck's consistency and grindgame since it allows for a draw 1-3 per turn. Finally with Runick, it gives Generaider an additional level 9 body to make XYZ plays with. Runick spells also break opponent's boards fairly well when played correctly in tandem with the other archetypes, especially when Sleipnir is summoned, since it can either banish a card on the field or be material for Laevateinn's XYZ superpoly. Runick offers solid defensive options, with Hugin protecting against destruction effects, Munin protecting from targeting effects and Geri dissuading the opponent from attacking. 
 
The rest of the deck is composed of STAPLES. The usual "Maxx C Minigame" package is included along with the Psy-Frame package allowing for maximum chance to win the annoying but mandatory cockroach interactions. Thankfully, this deck plays really well into Maxx C and Nibiru, since it doesn't have to summon a lot per turn - it can simply activate either Boss Stage or Fountain and pass. Nibiru and Imperm are included as Crossout targets. 
 
43 cards are included in the deck since everything important (like Boss Stage and Fountain) is highly searchable and to reduce the chances of drawing into garnets like Psy-Frame Driver or Generaider Harr/Utgarda. Even if you draw into these garnets, they can be used as discard cost from hand when searching Fountain with Hugin. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of Generaider Runick is to control/banish your opponent's resources until they surrender or deck-out. In certain situations, you can also enter the battle phase and OTK your opponent with your army of Generaider bosses/R9NK 9s when your opponent is helpless enough and they haven't surrendered yet. The ridiculous resource advantage and control options each archetype gives the duelist should win them the duel in most circumstances. 
 
Generaiders function as a control strategy, negating and interrupting your opponent until your giant beatsticks can attack for game. Generaider combos are simple since the strategy is so straightforward and with Runick cards, you have an easily accessible level 9 body since every Runick quick-play spell is like an "instant fusion!" These combos may be simple, but they end on an omni-negate, "XYZ superpoly," and possibly even handloops!
 
Here are the combo lines for Generaider:
 
Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses + Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light = Boss Stage and Laevatein
  1. Activate Vala's effect to summon herself by sending Mardel to the GY. 
  2. On summon, activate Vala's on-field effect to summon a Mardel from your GY/hand.
  3. Mardel searches Boss Stage. If you have another Generaider on hand, search Boss Quest instead, then search Boss Stage + Another Generaider S/T. 
  4. Activate Boss Stage.
  5. XYZ summon Laevatein using Vala + Mardel. 
Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses + Any level 9 Generaider + World Legacy Monstrosity = Boss Stage, 2 card hand-rip and Utopic Draco Future
  1. Activate Vala's effect to summon herself by sending level 9 Generaider to the GY. 
  2. On summon, activate Vala's on-field effect to summon a level 9 Generaider from your GY/hand.
  3. Activate Monstrosity targeting Vala on the field. Summon from deck Mardel and another level 9 Generaider. 
  4. Mardel searches Boss Stage. If you have another Generaider on hand, search Boss Quest instead, then search Boss Stage + Another Generaider S/T. 
  5. Activate Boss Stage.
  6. XYZ summon Enterblathnir. Activate it's effect to banish a random card from your opponent's hand. 
  7. Repeat step 6. Banish a second card from your opponent's hand. 
  8. XYZ summon Utopic Future by overlaying your two Enterblathnirs.
  9. XYZ summon Utopic Draco Future using your Utopic Future.
  10. XYZ summon Utopic Draco Future using your Utopic Future. 
The deck's endboard is generally is the same. It usually ends on Laevateinn + Boss Stage (ready to summon Harr/Utgarda on opponent's turn) but the duelist may end on Utopic Draco Future's monster negate/steal and a few set Runick cards. For some odd reason the endboard may also end on Runick Fountain and lean on the Runick strategy if you were unable to access Boss Stage.
 
With the unique control and resource advantage both Generaider and Runick offers, your opponent should wither away while you snowball to victory!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Similarly to Sky Striker, this is a toolbox control resource deck. It has a high skill ceiling since it factors in a player's decision making, resource management and match-up knowledge. Practice makes perfect with the deck!
  • If you want to save UR, you can get away with playing only 1 rather than 3 Mardel, since she is highly searchable in the deck anyways. 
  • Summon Laevateinn, Jormungandr or Utopic Draco Future in the Main Monster Zone rather than the Extra Monster Zone in case you need to summon a Runick monster for their toolbox protection effects. 
  • Generaider monsters are surprisingly excellent in breaking boards and baiting interruption. You can enter battle phase to clear your opponent's board with your high ATK Generaider bosses, suck up two cards using Laevateinn and continue your Runick plays during battlephase or main phase 2! 
  • This deck can generate so many bodies on board that it can easily OTK your opponent, especially since Boss Stage summons everyturn. If you feel your opponent cannot withstand your attack and they're out of resources, try to intentionally hold back from using Runick cards so you can enter the battle phase to finish them off!
  • Hugin's search effect for Runick Fountain isn't once per turn. If you can spare the cards, you can still search for Runick Fountain a second time! This makes Hugin ideal bait for your opponent's interruption. 
  • If your opponent Maxx "C,"'s you, stop summoning and don't take the maxx c challenge! Generaider Runick can end on their field spell and nothing more and still function properly. 
  • "World Gears" in the extra deck is a nuclear bomb that wipes both player's fields. Reset the board, then rebuild to set the momentum again in your favour!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
As a long time Generaider fan, I'm glad to present to you reading this another competitively viable Generaider strategy. Just the idea of being simultaneously an adventurer (Runick cards) and the boss (Generaider cards) just fulfills all the fantasy gameplay that I strive for in Yugioh! It's almost like I'm playing Final Fantasy or Dragon's Dogma in Yugioh form vs. my opponent! 
 
Going back to Norse Mythology, the arrival of Sleipnir, Odin's steed as a Yugioh card and Laevateinn, tbe harbringer of Ragnarok is just so thematically cool and badass. With Generaider Runick, YOU are the boss battle in the dueling arena!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Michael Walters

2005 Basic Format AST-TLM Horus
Skibidi

There is a lot here. Firstly, the common scareclaw line has a point right before you make Tri-Heart where you may have two level 3s on field, you can use these to go into the biker side of the deck, or go straight to the armored xyz. Goblins can get more 3s to possibly make the armored xyz. That is the general idea of the deck, go from scareclaw to goblin biker (instantly giving your oponent a stroke), then going into the armored xyz portion and passing. 

For non-engine I am running some bassic cards like Imperm and Ash, though I think the Ghost Belle may be a better fit than some cards. Forbidden is a nice board breaker, but evenly is very good. The only issue is that going second, you want to OTK with Tri-Heart so having to skip and do everything in main-phase 2 is a little rough. Also, if you're Light-heart is hit by Imperm, you can Droplet it to dodge.

Tech picks, rank 3 xyz monsters are good if you're tri-heart blows up somehow helps remedy your board and at least you can end on a No. 75. Fortune Tune can be a time win con? Spider is to help recover from Nib which an oponent may side into. Dharc is great because he can activate your eXceed, you can easily access him with the Light-Heart or Reichheart. Heres hoping they add a dark Goblin rider, I would be increadibly happy if the Merciless was a dark instead of a water, but o-well. You can side into the Twinsaw in heavily link heavy decks and it does not impose on the Armor Xyz trap effect. The Dogmatika Punishment, plus Rank 6 Goblin Biker is if you want to go heavier into the Goblin side of things, in whichcase you can dump the eXceeds for punishments to send the Rank 6 then use its effect to come back. If biulding the deck this way I would maybe add some of the Armored Xyz spell to capitalize off of Punishment, or maybe cut Punishment and run the Grand Bash instead since you can search it off of Big Gabonga. 

There are a ton of small synergies in this deck so I'll list a few of them:

1) Tri-Heart has a down pointing arrow and can co-link with Pheonix to net a draw. Notably, this is not the case for Unicorn, but I am running it anyways as a card you can go into for the bounce alone. 

2) Xyz Armor Torpedo detaches for a draw, which if you detach the scareclaw 3s may come back with an arrival.

3) You can use Sploder as a target for Visas and then go into Astraloud if you have Reichheart, which you should always try to. Sploder has a grave effet to come back too. 

4) You can discard a Visas for Forbidden droplet and go into an Astraloud that way. 

5) D-Barrier can only target one of these, if Xyz, just play a brickier Scareclaw and maybe Astraloud, if Link, get two threes, make a xyz and go into the armored xyz line and maybe Astraloud. Always maybe go into Astraloud, even if you don't get hit by D-barrier.

6) When special summoning the Goblins from the graveyard, if you do it in defense you can get three cards in defense real fast for your Reichheart which can get you a draw. Though this may not come up as often as generally Reichheart will be in play before the goblins. 

7) The Full Armored attach effect can allow you to detach for a goblin's summon effect later. Though thats not the most useful, it is just another line you can use. 

Cons:

The deck is a little more bricky than any of these pure, the Visas, armor xyz trap, multiple bikers, and multiple eXceeds can really suck to draw into. I am only running Visas cause I love Astraloud. 

The deck falls to Nibiru, which is why we play a Link Spider, but it can still really suck even with the Link Spider.

You need multiple of the Scareclaw links so extra deck space is a little tight. I am running multiple of them for the clap back. 

You may run out of main monster space, in general you need to be conscious about your zones, which I am not. 

 

End board is real elastic, peak is Tri-heart in extra monster-zone, Gabonga, Astraloud, Xyz Armor Fortress, two of the scareclaws (preferably Astra and Belone) with a Sclash or Twinsaw and a Full-Armored Xyz set. This is a deck that I will be playing more of in the future and updating. Any feedback is well appreciated.

deck_excerpt: Engage in chaotic cosmic conquest - where technology and magic pilot you to supremacy!
deck_description:
Dive into a universe of strategic supremacy with "GOAT Gradius - Option? Switch!" Structure Deck. Unleash the formidable "Gradius" and call upon its "Option" squadrons for rapid-fire support. Capitalize on the LIGHT and DARK dichotomy by deploying the enigmatic "Chaos Sorcerer," turning the tides of battle by banishing threats to distant galaxies.

Optimize your attack with "Opti-Camouflage Armor," turning your "Gradius' Option" into undetectable phantoms capable of striking directly at your opponent's Life Points. And when the situation demands a shift in strategy, metamorphose your fleet into the devastating "Thousand-Eyes Restrict," absorbing the power of any who dare oppose you.

But the tactical diversity doesn't end there. The side deck is a gateway to an alternative universe, where "Zombyra the Dark" and "King of the Swamp" lay in wait. By exchanging parts of your squadron, you can summon "The Last Warrior from Another Planet," sealing the summoning space-time continuum and forcing your adversaries into a corner from which there is no escape.

Key Combos and Techniques:

  • Set the scene with "Gradius" and elevate its attack with "Limiter Removal" to swiftly deplete your enemy's Life Points.
  • "Creature Swap" can turn the tables by trading an "Option" for a stronger foe, only to destroy the hijacked enemy with your bolstered arsenal.
  • Utilize "Metamorphosis" on an "Option" to summon "Thousand-Eyes Restrict," absorbing your opponent's monsters and creating an impenetrable wall of defense.
  • Prepare for a universe shift by side-decking into an anti-summoning strategy, trading aerial assaults for grounded supremacy with "The Last Warrior from Another Planet."
  • Prepare for a battle that transcends the stars. Whether you're weaving through asteroid fields with "Gradius" or bringing an abrupt halt to enemy reinforcements with "The Last Warrior from Another Planet," "GOAT Gradius - Option? Switch!" is your ticket to intergalactic domination in the GOAT format arena.

Gameplay + Combos in the video below

Like Tri-Brigade, Spright is one of the most splashable engines in Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel 2024. There are so many different deck profiles, each as fun and competent as the next. In today's video, we're trying a combination of a few of them by playing them together with Hero Kid, Melffys and Live Twins. I feel as though each of them has a place in this deck and helps it do what it does best, spamming Lv2s to the field baby! The Hero Kids allow you to make multiple Rank 2s. The Live Twins are 1-card starters. The Melffy's provide you with a negate and pseudo-grave lock. What's better is that this deck can run both Dimension Shifter and Herald of the Arc Light meaning that it also functions as a makeshift Anti-Meta deck. What's to to love?

A budget option i made for my brother as his first starter deck to get into yugioh. I replaced the Bonfires with 3x Small World and 2x Where Art Thou, it's less consistent but it works decently if well played. The Diabellstar Engine is replaced by a small Fire Kings package to serve as extender when needed.

Earlie Pitknight is a very low cost replacement for SP Little Knight. I opted for a small Super Poly package with Garura and Mud Dragon as a way of boardbreaking for the time being (in testing with decent results), once we get diabellstar we'll replace the Super Polys with Nibirus and the 2 extra deck monsters with Borreload Savage Dragon (Diabellstar's Synchro) and Salamangreat Raging Phoenix.

Sinful Spoils of subversion is there as a way to deal with annoying monster that cannot be destroyed by effects nor given back to the hand easily like Shaddoll Winda.

See my duels: 005-792-591

This is my new zombie deck with a combination of Shiranui and Tearlaments.

The deck's objective is simple, to prevent the opponent from being able to summon monsters using the effect of A Masterful Mayakashi Shiranui Saga.So we want to bring this letter as quickly as possible. And negating the effect of banishing monsters on your field.

Tearlaments cards are here to populate as many cards as possible in the graveyard, once the right cards are there, it's easy to do countless summons. And also, because of the ease of summoning these cards.

One of the big problems I was facing with most zombie decks was taking a handtrap at the beginning of the game for the 3 main cards that throw monsters into the cemetery and make things happen, and Tearlaments fit like a glove here, in addition to filling the cemetery, is another monster on the field that easily turns into a zombie due to the effect of Zombieworld, in addition to often being the target of an Ash, which gives us a chance to use the main cards of the deck.

I don't even need to say why Fenrir is here, besides being extremely strong and simple to summon, its effect of banishing cards is a great complement to Balerdroch and other cards that aim to banish monsters on the opponent's field, in addition to its effect that easily brings the Tearlaments Kashtira to your hand.
